entry.title: mac: speculative fix the fullscreen lockup
entry.content:
The trigger condition of this bug is still unknown, but this is a

potential event sequence that results in an infinite loop:



Assume two monitors A and B and the following happens in sequence:



0. B is on active space.

1. User switches space on A.

2. On A, NSToolbarFullScreenWindow becomes key

3. On B, we activate the browser window by -makeKeyAndOrderFront.

4. A space on A becomes active as a result of step 1

5. On B, NSToolbarFullScreenWindow becomes key as a result of step 3.

6. On A, we activate the browser window by -makeKeyAndOrderFront.

7. A space on B becomes active as a result of step 5.

8. goes to step 2 as a result of step 6.



The key of this happening is that there is a timing gap between a

NSToolbarFullScreenWindow becoming key and the space becoming active.

As a result, we activate the wrong browser window and enter a loop.



This CL speculatively fixes the bug by ensuring that the

NSToolbarFullScreenWindow that became key is on the same space of the

browser window being activated.



I verified the fix by running it locally for my workflow for hours. The

bug does not seem to reproduce anymore.



Bug: 1496367

entry.title: Move LevenshteinDistance() to base/strings
entry.content:
The Levenshtein distance is a commonly used measure for the similarity

of two strings, a and b. It is defined as the minimum number of

insert/remove/replace operations to convert from a to b. It can be

computed with a well-known dynamic programming algorithm in O(|a|*|b|).



In Chromium, this measure currently used in Ash, Autofill and SSLErrors.

components/compose is also planning to use it.

This CL unifies existing usages by moving Autofill's implementation to

base/strings.



All three existing uses only test if the Levenshtein distance is below

some small constant k. In this case, the computation can improved to

O(min(|a|, |b|) * k + k), using a variant of the dynamic programming

algorithm. Autofill's algorithm actually implements this, using an

optional third parameter. This parameter is used to improve the runtime

of the two other use cases.



Code-technically, this CL:

- Defines a function LevenshteinDistance() for std::string_view and

std::u16string_view arguments using a templated implementation.

- Combines all existing unit tests in a base_unittest.

entry.title: Multiplanar: Update GLCommonImageBackingFactory::GetFormatInfo
entry.content:
Update GLCommonImageBackingFactory::GetFormatInfo to return a vector

of format info for multiplanar formats based on corresponding planes'

formats being supported. This avoids basing the logic in AngleVulkan

and GLTexture shared image backings on multiplanar format constants

and instead uses the formats channel format and plane configs for

returning vector of FormatInfos.



This allows us to decouple the reliance of supported format logic in

backings from multiplanar shared image constants (which assume certain

channel format and plane configs) to various combinations of channel

formats and plane configs which can be used with hardware GMBs

through software video decode for pixel upload (VideoResourceUpdater).

entry.title: Rewrite ProgramInfoManager without type-punning
entry.content:
Type-punning via pointer casts is UB by strict aliasing and because the

pointers may not be aligned. UBSan flags the latter. (There is no strict

aliasing sanitizer and Chromium doesn't enable it.)

practices, this CL enables the relevant feature flags by default and

entry.title: Fenced frames: Do not repeat common checks for beacon sent to each
entry.content:
destination.



1. SendFencedFrameReportingBeaconInternal() contains checks that are

same for different destinations. For example, it checks whether the

current frame is active. Such checks, if fail, indicate none of the

beacons can be sent from this frame, regardless of its destination.



We call this function like this:



for (destination: destinations):

SendFencedFrameReportingBeaconInternal(destination)



So checks are unnecessarily repeated for each destination.



2. For MaybeSendFencedFrameAutomaticReportingBeacon(), these checks

have already been done in its function body, before calling

SendFencedFrameReportingBeaconInternal(). There is no need to repeat

them in SendFencedFrameReportingBeaconInternal().



This CL moves those checks to another function IsFencedFrameReportingFromRendererAllowed(). It is called in the two

endpoints that deal with reportEvent() calls from renderers.



Why not calling this also for MaybeSendFencedFrameAutomaticReportingBeacon(), which is from the

browsers?



- The automatic beacon is allowed to be sent from ad components (with

restriction on event type), but reportEvent() is not allowed to be invoked from ad components. So the checks are slightly different.

- For calls from renderers, these checks should already been done at

the renderers side. If they fail in browsers, it mean the renderer has

been compromised so we need to kill it. For automatic beacon we don't

have to kill the renderer.

- There are metrics recording logics nested in the checks in

MaybeSendFencedFrameAutomaticReportingBeacon(). It is possible to have those checks inside one common function shared by both event reporting

requests initiated from renderers and browsers. But I think it makes

the code harder to understand.



After this change, we have a clear boundary between:

1. Checks that are specific to individual destination, event data,

event type, etc. For example, whether the event data exceeds the

length limit. They are checked in

SendFencedFrameReportingBeaconInternal() and its downstreams.

2. Checks that are irrelevant to the above parameters. For example,

whether the frame is active. They are checked before the call to

SendFencedFrameReportingBeaconInternal().



The will help my next CL to address the issues in fenced frame

event reporting negative tests. See crbug below. My plan is to use

a TestFuture to get whether a beacon is sent for a destination.



- If any of category 2 checks fail, I can directly set the future to

empty, indicating none of beacons get sent to the destinations.



- If all category 2 checks pass, the bool return value from

SendFencedFrameReportingBeaconInternal() tells us where the beacon is

sent for this specific destination.



Note SendFencedFrameReportingBeaconToCustomURL() misses the check

on event data length. In this CL, the length check is moved to

SendFencedFrameReportingBeaconInternal() so this gets fixed

automatically.

entry.title: Stop syncing WalletMetadataSpecifics of type ADDRESS
entry.content:
Please read the description of crrev.com/c/5005347 for context first.

This CL removes code responsible for syncing the metadata of server

addresses through AUTOFILL_WALLET_METADATA. The billing address IDs of

credit cards remain untouched.



More specifically, this CL removes the client-side handling of

WalletMetadataSpecifics of type ADDRESS. On the server-side, any writes

for type of metadata specifics are already dropped (cl/547504099).

Since existing data (written before cl/547504099) was not deleted yet,

WalletMetadataSpecifics of type ADDRESS can still reach the wallet

metadata sync bridge during initial syncs.



From a technical perspective, this CL:

- Stops observing AutofillProfileChanged() events in the

AutofillWalletMetadataSyncBridge, since no server profile metadata

changes should be uploaded anymore.

- When integrating remote changes (MergeRemoteChanges()), any changes of

type ADDRESS are ignored. The (Add|Remove|Update)ServerAddressMetadata

calls that write to AutofillTable are removed.

- Special treatment around WalletMetadataSpecifics::has_converted is

removed (whether to prefer local or remote data), since this is a

field that's only used for address metadata [1].

- Any unit tests around server address metadata syncing are removed.

Tests around billing address ids are kept. They keep referencing

addresses.

- No sync integration tests are touched, since crrev.com/c/5005347

already removed them.

- Like in crrev.com/c/5005347, the proto fields are kept.

entry.title: Use DROP TABLE IF EXISTS in AutofillTable
entry.content:
The code is inconsistent and drops tables in three different ways:

1. Just DROP TABLE x

2. DROP TABLE IF EXISTS x

As of this CL, DROP TABLE IF EXISTS is used everywhere. In the cases

that currently use pattern 1, this is a behavior change. However,

since the state of the table is out of our control (a user might

manually drop it), this is a desirable change.

entry.title: Make the CSS math operation nested after distributing a multiplication over a sum
entry.content:
Due to the fact that CSS math trees are binary in Blink,

when we distribute a multiplication over a sum:

A - B * (C + D)

We don't know about the minus: A - ..., as

B * (C + D)

is the right-hand side of the operation A - ....

So, when we distribute B, we end up with

A - B * C + B * D,

which is incorrect.

Instead, leave the distributed operation nested, e.g.:

A - (B * C + B * D).



Note: The serialization code will not add unneeded parentheses:

(A + B) -> A + B.



Fixed: 1499774

entry.title: Remove AUTOFILL_WALLET_DATA server address receival logic
entry.content:
Payment billing addresses (= "server addresses") are downstreamed to

Chrome via AUTOFILL_WALLET_DATA. The data is read-only on the client.

In the distant past (around 2014), these addresses were offered side-by-

side with regular Autofill addresses. In 2017, Autofill stopped exposing

these addresses directly, and instead started converting them to local

Autofill addresses.



With the launch of project Leipzig, the conversion logic and thus

downstreaming of server addresses became obsolete, as Leipzig makes the

same addresses available to Chrome via CONTACT_INFO.

Server-side, Payments is already in the process of stopping to send the

server addresses (see b/290265885).

This CL is the client-side counterpart, which removes the logic that

persists incoming server addresses.

The address conversion logic (the only remaining consumer of this data

in) was already removed in crrev.com/c/4922357.



While the downstreamed server addresses are read-only, Chrome instances

sync metadata (use count, etc) for them via AUTOFILL_WALLET_METADATA.

This behavior isn't touched by this CL for CL-size reasons, but will be

cleaned up in a follow-up.

Similarly, the downstreaming of billing address ids for credit cards

via AUTOFILL_WALLET_DATA, and the syncing of billing address ids via

AUTOFILL_WALLET_METADATA is untouched by this CL.



See go/autofill-deprecate-payment-address-conversion and [1] for more

in depth details.



From a technical point of view, this CL does the following:

- Removes the handling of incoming AutofillWalletSpecifics::

POSTAL_ADDRESS in AutofillWalletSyncBridge: Incoming data of this

type is simply ignored and nothing is written to AutofillTable

anymore. See PopulateWalletTypesFromSyncData() in

autofill_sync_bridge_util.cc.

- Removes all unit tests around this behavior.

- Simplifies all single-client sync integration tests that rely on this

behavior: Most of these tests are not specific to server addresses,

but instead test what happens when server cards, server addresses,

cloud tokens, etc are received. As such, only the server addresses

parts of the tests are removed.

One test, DoNotConvertServerAddressAgain is removed completely, since

the conversion logic no longer exists (see CL linked above).

- Receiving a server addresses also created entries for the address

metadata [2]. For this reason, all checks around server address

metadata are removed from the sync integration tests.

This is going somewhat beyond the scope of this CL, since the code in

AUTOFILL_WALLET_METADATA is untouched. But fixing these tests

temporarily doesn't seem worth the effort. Arguably, these checks

shouldn't exist anymore, since:

- The server-side drops incoming server address metadata changes.

- The client doesn't send server address metadata changes anymore

since Leipzig was launched.

- The fields the proto (autofill_specifics.proto) are kept, because the

proto needs to be in sync with the server-side. Since some

server-side code still references it, TODOs are added.

- Removes all the sync integration test helper functions from

wallet_helper that became unused by this CL.

- (No two-client sync integration tests are touched, since no relevant

tests around this behavior exist. It was already cleaned up in

crrev.com/c/4742310).



[1] https://docs.google.com/document/d/1CC7hPJJDdwaS7Jxz8YaT4no0gtBg2L9zG7pnNAwVvgA/edit?usp=sharing&resourcekey=0-1Da1ItiVxBkGmzdNi4rLaA

[2] https://source.chromium.org/chromium/chromium/src/+/main:components/autofill/core/browser/webdata/autofill_table.cc;l=2722;drc=90e7f8283efed57081a42f445d32d5ab3d063bfe
